### âœ… **Summary**

**Scripting** is writing small programs to automate tasks.

**Shell scripting** is writing scripts in the terminal (using Bash or Zsh).

You can:
- Write a script with `nano script.sh`  
- Add a shebang: `#!/bin/bash`  
- Use `chmod +x script.sh` to make it executable  
- Run it with `./script.sh`  
- Use `echo`, `cat`, `>` (redirect), `&` (background), and `whoami`, `pwd`, `date` to do things

Step-by-Step: Exit nano and Return to the Terminal

Youâ€™re in nano, editing a file
To save the file:
Press Ctrl+O (hold Ctrl, press O)
Then press Enter to confirm the filename

To exit nano:
Press Ctrl+X
Thatâ€™s Ctrl and X together
âœ… After pressing Ctrl+X, youâ€™ll be back in the terminal, at your normal prompt.


You can rewrite and erase text in nano.

Letâ€™s clarify:

âœ… You can:
Type new text
Delete text using the backspace or delete key
Move the cursor using the arrow keys
Cut and paste using Ctrl+K (cut), Ctrl+U (paste)
Go to a specific line using Ctrl+_ (then type the line number)
 

âŒ But you cannot:
Delete text by pressing Delete (on some keyboards, it doesnâ€™t work)
Use Backspace if your keyboard is set up differently
Use Ctrl+C to cancel â€” it might just copy text
 \

âœ… How to Delete Text in nano
Move the cursor to the character you want to delete
Press Backspace (the key that erases characters to the left)
Or press Delete (the key that erases characters to the right)
Or press Ctrl+K to cut the current line
Or press Ctrl+U to paste it back
\

âœ… How to Rewrite Text in nano
Move the cursor to where you want to edit
Type to overwrite the text
Or press Backspace to delete and retype
You can edit the file just like you would in any text editor.

âœ… Pro Tip:
If you want to clear the entire file, you can:

Press Ctrl+K repeatedly to cut all lines
Or press Ctrl+X and then press n when it asks to save (to discard changes)
But if you want to keep changes, press Ctrl+O, then Enter, then Ctrl+X.

